				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{AR1}\otimes \mathrm{AR1}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M148"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">AR</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow><mml:mo>⊗</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">AR</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:mrow></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="122_2019_3424_Article_IEq69.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula></title>
        <p id="Par30">The autoregressive model of order 1 (AR1) for the Gaussian vector <inline-formula id="IEq70"><alternatives><tex-math id="M149">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\varvec{x}} = (x_1,\ldots , x_\mathrm{r})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M150"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">x</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>=</mml:mo><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mn>1</mml:mn></mml:msub><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:mo>…</mml:mo><mml:mo>,</mml:mo><mml:msub><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">r</mml:mi></mml:msub><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="122_2019_3424_Article_IEq70.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> is defined as:<disp-formula id="Equ11"><alternatives><tex-math id="M151">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
