      <sec id="Sec12">
        <title>Gaussian random fields and the Matérn model</title>
        <p id="Par32">In the model described above, the spatial variation was modelled as discrete, meaning that the model only considers data on a fixed field trial layout, possibly allowing the distance between rows to be different from the distance between columns. Assuming a continuous field for the spatial variation is, however, more realistic and allows the spatial variation to be modelled at any observed distance or field trial layout.</p>
        <p id="Par33">Continuously indexed Gaussian random fields play an important role in spatial statistical modelling and geostatistics. In the field <inline-formula id="IEq81"><alternatives><tex-math id="M175">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathscr {D}\in \mathbb {R}^d$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M176"><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="script">D</mml:mi><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:msup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="double-struck">R</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mi>d</mml:mi></mml:msup></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="122_2019_3424_Article_IEq81.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> with coordinates <inline-formula id="IEq82"><alternatives><tex-math id="M177">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\varvec{s}} \in \mathscr {D}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M178"><mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">s</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo>∈</mml:mo><mml:mi mathvariant="script">D</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="122_2019_3424_Article_IEq82.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula>, the continuously indexed Gaussian random field <inline-formula id="IEq83"><alternatives><tex-math id="M179">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$x({\varvec{s}})$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M180"><mml:mrow><mml:mi>x</mml:mi><mml:mo stretchy="false">(</mml:mo><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="bold-italic">s</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mo stretchy="false">)</mml:mo></mml:mrow></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="122_2019_3424_Article_IEq83.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> has a joint Gaussian distribution for all finite collections <inline-formula id="IEq84"><alternatives><tex-math id="M181">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
